What are the parameters for LCDM?

The Lambda Cold Dark Matter (LCDM) model is a cosmological model that describes the expansion and evolution of the universe. It is based on the theories of general relativity and the standard model of particle physics, and it assumes that the universe is composed of a mix of ordinary matter, dark matter, and dark energy. The LCDM model is characterized by several parameters, including the Hubble constant, which is a measure of the expansion rate of the universe, and the densities of matter and dark energy in the universe, which are typically expressed as the fraction of the critical density of the universe that they represent. These parameters can be determined by observations of the universe and are used to make predictions about its evolution and structure.


