What are the most distant objects we measure using parallax?

The most distant objects that can be measured using parallax are nearby stars in the Milky Way galaxy. Parallax is a method of measuring the distance to an object by observing its apparent shift in position against the background of more distant objects. It relies on the fact that the observer's position changes over the course of a year, due to the Earth's orbit around the Sun. By measuring the apparent shift in position of a nearby star, it is possible to calculate its distance from the Earth. The accuracy of this method is limited by the distances involved and the precision of the measurements, so it is not possible to use parallax to measure the distances to objects that are much further away than the nearest stars.


What other model independent methods of determining distance after parallax?

After parallax, the next most accurate model-independent method for measuring distances to objects in the universe is the standard candle method. The standard candle method is based on the observation that certain types of objects, such as certain types of stars or explosions, have a well-defined intrinsic brightness. By measuring the apparent brightness of these objects, it is possible to determine their distance from the observer. The standard candle method is based on the inverse square law, which states that the apparent brightness of an object decreases with the square of its distance from the observer. This method can be used to measure distances to objects that are much further away than the nearest stars, but it is limited by the precision of the measurements and the availability of standard candles with known intrinsic brightness.


For example, using Cephid variable stars? 

Yes, that is correct. Cepheid variable stars are one example of a type of object that can be used as a standard candle to measure distances in the universe. Cepheid variable stars are a type of star that pulsates periodically, and the period of their pulsations is directly related to their intrinsic brightness. By measuring the period of pulsation of a Cepheid variable star and comparing it to its apparent brightness, it is possible to determine its distance from the observer. This method has been used to measure distances to galaxies in the local universe and has provided important constraints on our understanding of the expansion and evolution of the universe.


