What is the expansion rate of the universe?

The expansion rate of the universe is a measure of how quickly the universe is expanding. It is commonly expressed in terms of the Hubble constant, which is a unit of measurement that describes the rate at which the universe is expanding. The current best estimate of the Hubble constant is approximately 73.5 kilometers per second per megaparsec. This means that for every 3.26 million light-years that a galaxy is from us, it is moving away from us at a rate of 73.5 kilometers per second. The expansion rate of the universe is an important parameter in cosmology, and it is used to make predictions about the evolution and structure of the universe.


What is the value of Hubble's constant according to measurements of the CMB?

The value of the Hubble constant that is derived from measurements of the cosmic microwave background radiation (CMB) is slightly lower than the value that is derived from other methods. The current best estimate of the Hubble constant from CMB measurements is approximately 67.4 kilometers per second per megaparsec. This value is slightly lower than the value of 73.5 kilometers per second per megaparsec that is derived from other methods, such as measuring the distances to galaxies using standard candles. The discrepancy between these two values is known as the Hubble tension, and it is currently a topic of active research in cosmology.


Yep, that's the Hubble tension alright.

Yes, that is correct. The discrepancy between the value of the Hubble constant that is derived from measurements of the cosmic microwave background radiation (CMB) and the value that is derived from other methods is known as the Hubble tension. This tension is currently a topic of active research in cosmology, and it has implications for our understanding of the expansion and evolution of the universe. Some possible explanations for the tension include systematic errors in the measurements, variations in the expansion rate of the universe over time, or the existence of new physics beyond the current standard cosmological model. Further observations and research will be needed to fully understand the nature of the Hubble tension and its implications for cosmology.


