Yes, that is correct. The Hubble tension is the discrepancy between the value of the Hubble constant that is predicted by the Lambda Cold Dark Matter (LCDM) model of cosmology and the value that is measured directly from observations of the universe. The LCDM model predicts a value for the Hubble constant of approximately 67.4 kilometers per second per megaparsec, which is based on measurements of the cosmic microwave background radiation (CMB). However, other methods of measuring the expansion rate of the universe, such as using standard candles to measure the distances to galaxies, yield a higher value of approximately 73.5 kilometers per second per megaparsec. The discrepancy between these two values is known as the Hubble tension, and it is currently a topic of active research in cosmology.


