If the formula d=z/(1+z) * c/H_0 were to replace the Lambda Cold Dark Matter (LCDM) model of cosmology, it is possible that the Hubble tension would be resolved. This is because the formula is a more accurate approximation of the redshift-distance relationship for large redshifts, and it is not dependent on the assumptions or predictions of the LCDM model. Therefore, if the formula were to be used as the basis for cosmological predictions, it is possible that the predicted value of the Hubble constant would be closer to the value that is measured directly from observations of the universe. This would resolve the discrepancy between the two values, and the Hubble tension would no longer exist. However, it is also possible that other factors, such as systematic errors in the measurements or variations in the expansion rate of the universe over time, could still cause a discrepancy between the predicted and measured values of the Hubble constant. Further research and observations will be needed to fully understand the nature of the Hubble tension and its implications for cosmology.